post_text: Here’s your summer challenge! Read for just 15 minutes a day.
shared_text:
Patten Free Library
June 8 at 7:00 AM ·

Wondering what to do on your first day of vacation? Join the commmunity of readers participating in Patten Free Library's Summer Reading Program. Commit to the simple habit of reading 15 minutes a day! Check out the video for all the reaons why. Get reading logs and program details on our website or through curbside pickup.

post_text: We’re preparing for the Chickadee Award! K students listened to a past winner, The Memoirs of a Parrot by Devin Scillian, and completed a sample booklet page. Drawing a favorite part of the story.
text: We’re preparing for the Chickadee Award! K students listened to a past winner, The Memoirs of a Parrot by Devin Scillian, and completed a sample booklet page. Drawing a favorite part of the story.

post_text: 5th graders figured out familiar book titles using emojis. This fun and engaging activity called for critical thinking skills and teamwork. Can you guess this title? 🤴 ⛵️ 🏝 👹👹

post_text: Today students casted their final vote for our Mock Caldecott 2020. We connected with other students through a digital tool called Padlet. Students were able to share their thoughts as well as respond to others. Stayed tuned to hear which book will win the WBS Mock Caldecott 2020!
text: Today students casted their final vote for our Mock Caldecott 2020. We connected with other students through a digital tool called Padlet. Students were able to share their thoughts as well as respond to others. Stayed tuned to hear which book will win the WBS Mock Caldecott 2020!

post_text: In preparation for our Mock Caldecott, students worked on the following learning target, I can critique illustrations using the Caldecott criteria. We used past winners and honor books.
text: In preparation for our Mock Caldecott, students worked on the following learning target, I can critique illustrations using the Caldecott criteria. We used past winners and honor books.

post_text: Third grade students listened to Rabbit’s Gift by George Shannon. We then practiced using Destiny, our online catalog, to search for books and use call numbers to identify if a book is a picture book or nonfiction book.
text: Third grade students listened to Rabbit’s Gift by George Shannon. We then practiced using Destiny, our online catalog, to search for books and use call numbers to identify if a book is a picture book or nonfiction book.

post_text: Today in library, first graders enjoyed these two alphabet books, ABC Dream by Kim Krans and Alphabet City by Stephen T. Johnson. It was a great way to make a connection to their expedition work in the classroom and learn some new vocabulary words.
text: Today in library, first graders enjoyed these two alphabet books, ABC Dream by Kim Krans and Alphabet City by Stephen T. Johnson. It was a great way to make a connection to their expedition work in the classroom and learn some new vocabulary words.

post_text: This week, in 4th grade library, we read Red and Lulu by Matt Tavares. A stunning picture book that I highly recommend. We then used the Rockefeller Center website to gather more information by using website features such as timelines and photo captions. https://www.rockefellercenter.com/holidays/rockefeller-center-christmas-tree-lighting/

post_text: The Mustard Seed Book Fair is setting up this afternoon! Tomorrow all students will have a chance to preview the fair and fill out a wish list. Book Fair will be open Monday, November 25 from 12:00 - 7:00.

post_text: Today in library, Miss Marco’s class used images (primary sources) to help understand Balloons Over Broadway by Melissa Sweet.
text: Today in library, Miss Marco’s class used images (primary sources) to help understand Balloons Over Broadway by Melissa Sweet.

post_text: First graders practiced sequencing after reading One is a Feast for Mouse by Judy Cox.
text: First graders practiced sequencing after reading One is a Feast for Mouse by Judy Cox.

post_text: Today we read Fangsgiving by Ethan Long. A fun story about Vladimir the vampire and his family visiting for Thanksgiving. Then students created their own Vladimir following a directed drawing activity.
text: Today we read Fangsgiving by Ethan Long. A fun story about Vladimir the vampire and his family visiting for Thanksgiving. Then students created their own Vladimir following a directed drawing activity.

post_text: Today in Mrs. Jarvis’ library class we worked on the learning target I can use a call number to locate books. We started with sorting spine labels. Then worked on a call number scavenger hunt.
text: Today in Mrs. Jarvis’ library class we worked on the learning target I can use a call number to locate books. We started with sorting spine labels. Then worked on a call number scavenger hunt.

post_text: This week 4th and 5th graders read Sergeant Reckless: The True Story of the Little Horse Who Became a War Hero by Patricia McCormick. In 4th grade we focused on how illustrations can provide readers with more information. The illustrations by Iacopo Bruno are amazing! In 5th grade we focused on the book’s back matter, the author’s note and bibliography, and gathering more information from this part of the book.
text: This week 4th and 5th graders read Sergeant Reckless: The True Story of the Little Horse Who Became a War Hero by Patricia McCormick. In 4th grade we focused on how illustrations can provide readers with more information. The illustrations by Iacopo Bruno are amazing! In 5th grade we focused on the book’s back matter, the author’s note and bibliography, and gathering more information from this part of the book.

post_text: Last week, we used the magic of technology to hear a story read by the author! Mrs. Harris’s class enjoyed Hubknuckles written and read by Emily Herman. We used Google Hangout to connect with Emily and the second graders at Georgetown School.
